<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15029</anchor> <rss>jms-009P.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Log</taxon> <addr>jms-009P</addr>  <route>jms-009P.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="hofmann-streicher-1997.xml" type="local" title="Lifting Grothendieck universes">Hofmann–Streicher lifting</link> and comonadicity of fibrations</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="2023-09-15" type="external">Yesterday</link>, I happened upon the <link href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HBaQIQhEotc" type="external">video</link> of <link href="pinorosolini.xml" type="local" title="Guiseppe Rosolini">Guiseppe Rosolini</link>’s talk at the <link href="chapman-grothendieck-2022.xml" type="local" title="Grothendieck Conference">Grothendieck Conference</link>, and I finally got around to looking a <link href="emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.xml" type="local" title="A comonad for Grothendieck fibrations">preprint</link> that it refers to:</p>        <tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15030</anchor> <rss>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023</addr>  <route>emmenegger-mesiti-rosolini-streicher-2023.xml</route>  <authors><author><link href="jacopoemmenegger.xml" type="local">Jacopo Emmenegger</link></author><author><link href="lucamesiti.xml" type="local">Luca Mesiti</link></author><author><link href="pinorosolini.xml" type="local">Guiseppe Rosolini</link></author><author><link href="thomasstreicher.xml" type="local">Thomas Streicher</link></author> </authors> <title>A comonad for Grothendieck fibrations</title> <meta name="doi">10.48550/arXiv.2305.01474</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We study the 2-category theory of Grothendieck fibrations in the 2-category of functors <tex>\mathbf{Cat} ^{ \to }</tex>. After redrawing a few general results in that context, we show that fibrations over a given base are pseudo-coalgebras for a 2-comonad on  <tex>{ \mathbf{Cat} } _{ / B }</tex>. We use that result to explain how an arbitrary fibration is equivalent to one with a splitting.</p></mainmatter> </tree>  
<p>What the paper proves is that in addition to fibrations being 2-monadic over displayed categories, they are also <em>2-comonadic</em>. I noticed that the <link href="hofmann-streicher-1997.xml" type="local" title="Lifting Grothendieck universes">Hofmann–Streicher lifting</link> actually factors through this additional right 2-adjoint. This sounds like a promising path forward for my own attempts to generalize Hofmann–Streicher lifting to a 2-functor over an arbitrary 2-category.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15031</anchor> <rss>chapman-grothendieck-2022.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Conference</taxon> <addr>chapman-grothendieck-2022</addr>  <route>chapman-grothendieck-2022.xml</route> <date><year>2022</year> <month>5</month> </date>  <title>Grothendieck Conference</title> <meta name="external">https://www.chapman.edu/scst/conferences-and-events/grothendieck-conference.aspx</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Chapman University hosted a conference honoring and exploring the contributions of <link href="alexandergrothendieck.xml" type="local" title="Alexander Grothendieck">Alexander Grothendieck</link> to the field of Mathematics. This conference was sponsored by Chapman University and the University of Paris. We were honored to have our eminent guests here to speak to us on the revolutionary nature of <link href="alexandergrothendieck.xml" type="local" title="Alexander Grothendieck">Grothendieck</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15032</anchor> <rss>pinorosolini.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>pinorosolini</addr>  <route>pinorosolini.xml</route>   <title>Guiseppe Rosolini</title> <meta name="position">Professor of Mathematical Logic</meta><meta name="institution">Università degli Studi di Genova</meta><meta name="external">https://www.dima.unige.it/~rosolini/</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15033</anchor> <rss>hofmann-streicher-1997.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>hofmann-streicher-1997</addr>  <route>hofmann-streicher-1997.xml</route> <date><year>1997</year>  </date> <authors><author><link href="martinhofmann.xml" type="local">Martin Hofmann</link></author><author><link href="thomasstreicher.xml" type="local">Thomas Streicher</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting Grothendieck universes</title> <meta name="bibtex">@unpublished{hofmann-streicher-1997,
  author = {Hofmann, Martin and Streicher, Thomas},
